[[File:Complete-church-midnight-mass (3135957575).jpg|thumb|350px|Many Christians attend [[church service]]s on [[Christmas Eve]], the Christian [[Vigil#Eves_of_religious_celebrations|vigil]] that celebrates the [[Nativity of Jesus|birth of Jesus Christ]].<ref name="Jespersen2011">{{cite book|last=Jespersen|first=Knud J. V.|title=A History of Denmark|date=21 June 2011|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|language=English|isbn=9780230344174|page=91|quote=It is quite normal to go to church on Christmas Eve, and many people like to celebrate a christening or wedding in church. The Church is especially important at the end of a life; by far the majority of funerals are still conducted in a church by a minister.}}</ref>]]
{{Christianity|state=collapsed}}
'''Church attendance''' is a central religious practice for many [[Christians]]; some [[Christian denominations]], such as the [[Catholic Church]] require church attendance on the [[Lord's Day]] (Sunday); the [[Westminster Confession of Faith]] is held by the Reformed Churches and teaches [[first-day Sabbatarianism]],<ref name="Wigley1980">{{cite book|last=Wigley|first=John|title=The Rise and Fall of the Victorian Sunday|year=1980|publisher=Manchester University Press|language=English|isbn=9780719007941|page=800|quote=Following the formulation of the Westminster Confession, fully fledged Sabbatarianism quickly took root too, being embodied in an Act of 1661, then spreading northwards and westwards as the Highlands were opened up after the '45, during which time the doctrine lost its original force and vigour in the Lowlands.}}</ref> thus proclaiming the duty of public worship in keeping with the [[Remember the sabbath day, to keep it holy|Ten Commandments]].<ref name="McKim2011">{{cite book|last=McKim|first=Donald K.|title=More Presbyterian Questions, More Presbyterian Answers: Exploring Christian Faith|year=2011|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|isbn=9780664503086|page=72|quote=The Westminster Confession urges a strict observance of the Lord's Day as a day of rest and worship, away from "works, words, and thoughts" about "worldly employments and recreations." The whole time is to be devoted to "public and private exercises of [God's) worship, and in duties of necessity and mercy" (''BC'' 6.119). In the United States, many "blue laws" relating to Sunday originated from this general prescription observed by American Puritans of the Reformed tradition.}}</ref> Similarly, The General Rules of the Methodist Church also requires "attending upon all the ordinances of God" including "the public worship of God".<ref name="AbrahamKirby2009">{{cite book|last1=Abraham|first1=William J.|last2=Kirby|first2=James E.|title=The Oxford Handbook of Methodist Studies|date=24 September 2009|publisher=OUP Oxford|language=English|isbn=9780191607431|page=253}}</ref> Until 1791, the [[government of the United Kingdom]] required attendance at [[church service]]s of the [[Church of England]] (the mother Church of the [[Anglican Communion]] and a [[state Church]]) at least twice a year.<ref name="Day2014">{{cite book|last=Day|first=Cathy|title=Wiltshire Marriage Patterns 1754-1914: Geographical Mobility, Cousin Marriage and Illegitimacy|date=26 September 2014|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|language=English|isbn=9781443867924|page=198|quote=Attendance at an Anglican church service at least twice a year was a legal requirement for all people until 1791 and some parishioners endured the minimum church attendance requirement in order to avoid a fine.}}</ref> To this end, all major branches of [[Christianity]], however, encourage church attendance, with one Christian apostolate providing the following biblical imperatives: 
{{quote|The Bible tells us we need to attend church so we can worship God with other believers and be taught His Word for our spiritual growth ({{Bibleverse|Acts|2:42|NRSV}}; {{Bibleverse|Hebrews|10:25|NRSV}}). Church is the place where believers can love one another ({{Bibleverse|1 John|4:12|NRSV}}), encourage one another ({{Bibleverse|Hebrews|3:13|NRSV}}), "spur" one another ({{Bibleverse|Hebrews|10:24|NRSV}}), serve one another ({{Bibleverse|Galatians|5:13|NRSV}}), instruct one another ({{Bibleverse|Romans|15:14|NRSV}}), honor one another ({{Bibleverse|Romans|12:10|NRSV}}), and be kind and compassionate to one another ({{Bibleverse|Ephesians|4:32|NRSV}}).<ref name="Editor2014">{{cite book|last=Michael Houdmann|first=S. |title=Got Questions?: Bible Questions Answered|date=24 April 2014|language=English|isbn=9781490832739|page=180}}</ref>}}
The [[Lutheran]] Christian theologian [[:da:Balthasar Münter|Balthasar Münter]] stated that church attendance is the "foundation for the Christian life" as "the [[Christian Bible]] and the [[sacraments]] provide the framework for the faith"; he also states that it is important for believers because it aids in the prevention of [[backsliding]], as well as offers "the [[Communion (Christian)|company of other believers]]".<ref name="Roos2013">{{cite book|last=Roos|first=Merethe|title=Enlightened Preaching: Balthasar Münter’s Authorship 1772-1793|date=2013-03-08|publisher=[[Brill Academic Publishers]]|language=English |isbn=9789004249899|page=99}}</ref>

According to data from the European Social Survey in 2012 around a third of [[Christianity in Europe|European Christians]] say they attend services once a month or more.<ref name="economist">[https://www.economist.com/news/international/21684679-march-christianity-future-worlds-most-popular-religion-african Christianity and church attendance]</ref> Conversely about two-thirds of [[Christianity in Latin America|Latin American Christians]] and according to the [[World Values Survey]] about 90% of [[Christianity in Africa|African Christians]] (in [[Ghana]], [[Nigeria]], [[Rwanda]], [[South Africa]] and [[Zimbabwe]]) said they attended church regularly.<ref name="economist"/> The [[Gallup poll|Gallup International]], a self-reporting survey conducted via telephone, indicates that 37% of Americans report that they attend religious services weekly or near-weekly in 2013.<ref name=gallup>{{cite web|title=Religion: Gallup Historical Trends|url=http://www.gallup.com/poll/1690/religion.aspx|website=www.gallup.com|publisher=Gallup, Inc.|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> The [[Pew Research Center]] stated, however, that there is a "sharp increase in church attendance around the two most significant Christian holidays, [[Christmas]] and [[Easter]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2014/04/18/when-easter-and-christmas-near-more-americans-search-online-for-church/|title=When Easter and Christmas near, more Americans search online for "church"|last=Kuriakose|first=Noble|date=18 April 2014|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|language=English|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> As such, on Christmas (a [[Principal Feast]] in the [[Anglican Communion]], a [[holy day of obligation]] in the [[Catholic Church]] and a [[Liturgical_calendar_(Lutheran)#Festivals|Festival]] in the [[Lutheran Church]]es), LifeWay Research found that "six out of 10 Americans typically attend church".<ref name="Stetzer2015">{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/edstetzer/2015/december/what-is-church-attendance-like-during-christmastime-new-dat.html|title=What Is Church Attendance Like During Christmastime? New Data From LifeWay Research|last=Stetzer|first=Ed|date=14 December 2015|publisher=[[Christianity Today]]|language=English|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> Countries that hold or have held a policy of [[state atheism]] have actively discouraged church attendance, often [[Persecution of Christians in the Soviet Union|persecuting Christians who continued]] to worship.<ref>{{cite book|title=Athena Magazine, Issues 41-55|year=1991|publisher=International Studies Association|language=English|page=86|quote=It has also shrunk through the trial, 'as by fire', of decades of totalitarian state atheism, in which simply to profess the Christian Faith automatically ranked one as a dissident and church attendance was not infrequently the first step towards martyrdom.}}</ref>

== Statistics ==
